arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The Lucille P. Markey Charitable Trust collection is arranged in six series:

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Lucile P. Markey Charitable Trust (Markey Trust) was established as a limited term trust in the will of Lucille P. Markey in 1975. Incorporated as a Florida nonprofit organization 501(C)(3) status, the Trust began operation in October 1983. The Trust's office opened in Miami on January 1, 1984.

Mrs. Markey had several specific goals for her charitable giving which defined the nature of the Trust. Wishing to distribute the grant money in a relatively short period of time in order to fund current research, she was advised to create a charitable, limited term trust. Mrs. Markey wanted her fortune to be dedicated to the pursuit of "human health," which meant that trust contributions specifically targeted "basic biomedical research."

To ensure that her assets were distributed as she intended, Mrs. Markey nominated several close associates as trustees. Her attorney, Louis J. Hector, chaired the Board of Trustees, and Robert B. Glaser, M.D., became the Director of Medical Science. Other trustees included: William Sutter, representing Hopkins and Sutter, attorneys for Mrs. Markey's first husband Warren Wright; Laurette Heraty, Warren Wright's former secretary; and Margaret B. Glass, an employee of Calumet Farm. George Shinn subsequently replaced Laurette Heraty as board member.

During its fifteen-year operation, the Trust distributed over $500 million in three broad categories: Individual Grants, including scholarships and fellowships to younger researchers; Research Program Grants, to research centers conducting advanced research; and General Organizational Grants, toward the training and education of Ph.D.s and M.D.s pursuing careers in biomedical research.

Scholars received funding for up to three years' postdoctoral study and were offered a subsequent five years of support for faculty positions including salary and research funds. The first class of scholars began its tenure in July 1985. The final class selected (the seventh class overall) began its term in July 1991. Over the fifteen-year period of the Trust, 113 scholars were awarded grants. A comprehensive history of the Markey Trust is included in the Trust's Final Report, 1983-1996.

At the time of its creation,the Lucille P. Markey Charitable Trust's financial reserves placed it among the ten largest foundations in terms of charitable distribution. The terms of the Trust and its management of assets were explained in "Closing a Foundation: The Lucille P. Markey Charitable Trust" (Washington, D.C.: Council on Foundations, 2000), by John H. Dickason, and Duncan Neuhauser, available in the Rockefeller Archive Center's library collection.

The National Research Council Committee for the Evaluation of the Lucille P. Markey Visiting Fellows Program issued two publications concerning the Scholars Program: "Evaluation of the Markey Scholars Program" (2006) and "Bridging the Bed-Bunch Gap: Contributions of the Markey Trust" (2004) (both Washington, DC: National Academies Press).

The unique combination of the successful scholars selection process and the designation of the charitable trust as a limited term endeavor inspired several National Research Council reviews of the comprehensive program, including: Krystyna R. Isaacs, "The Lucille P. Markey Charitable Trust Scholars Program: Enhancing Philanthropy's Support of Biomedical Science"; and National Research Council, "Committee for the Evaluation of the Lucille P. Markey Charitable Trust Programs in Biomedical Sciences" (both Washington, DC: National Academies Press, 2006).

Lucille Parker was born on December 14, 1896, near Tollesboro, Kentucky; she was the youngest of seven children and the daughter of a tobacco farmer. In 1918, Lucille married Warren Wright, Sr., who had inherited the Calumet Baking Powder Company, as well as a horse farm near Lexington, Kentucky. The Wrights built this small inheritance into one of the most successful thoroughbred horse breeding and racing stables, Calumet Farm. After the death of Warren Wright in 1950, Lucille assumed control of the Farm. The bulk of Mrs. Markey's estate, however, derived from a large investment in oil and gas leases inherited from Warren Wright and drilled on the Waddell Ranch in western Texas.

Lucille Wright married her second husband, Admiral Gene Markey, in 1952 and continued to pursue her passion in horse breeding and horse racing. Over a period of nearly 50 years, Calumet won 8 Kentucky Derbies, 2 Triple Crowns, 3 Filly Triple Crowns, and had 148 stakes winners with total earnings of over $26 million.

During the reign of Calumet Farms, Mrs. Markey's charitable giving focused on the Bluegrass Boys' Ranch in Kentucky and the establishment of a cancer center at the University of Kentucky. The establishment of the Trust enabled Mrs. Markey to extend her interests in health to general support of biomedical institutions, with an emphasis on research, as opposed to health care delivery.

Mrs. Markey died on July 24, 1982. After Mrs. Markey's death, the Farm was inherited by Warren Wright, Jr.'s heirs. Mismanagement led to the forced sale of all land, horses, and equipment in 1992, when Calumet Farm filed for bankruptcy.

Mrs. Markey's second husband Admiral Gene Markey was a writer, producer, and Hollywood personality who achieved some notoriety in his personal life, if not in his attempt to become a recognized writer. Prior to his marriage to Lucille, he was married to three well-known actresses: Myrna Loy, Hedy Lamarr, and Joan Bennett. The papers of Admiral Gene Markey are housed at Skidmore College in Saratoga Springs, New York, and include the Markeys' personal library of horse literature.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection focuses upon grants awarded for biomedical research to institutions in the United States during 1983-1996. Grant records include correspondence regarding application criteria, financial awards, and periodic research reports. Administrative records detail program development and advisory committee decisions. A scrapbook, newspaper clippings, and photographs detail Calumet Farm, the horseracing concern which Mrs. Markey owned and operated.

accessrestrict.p: Open for research. The archival material has been reformatted to microfilm. Microfilm user copies are available for research.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This subseries includes files for the 113 scholars awarded grants to pursue basic biomedical research. Scholars' grants were awarded to individuals at the initial stages of their pursuit of study in postgraduate biomedical research. Each grant file is titled with the grantee's name followed by the grant number which indicates the year in which the grant began. The inclusive dates note the chronology of the reports and correspondence. Each file includes: scholar's transmittal sheet; statement of research goals; letters of recommendation from faculty sponsor, department chairperson or institutional officer, director of PhD training program or residency program director; and other letters of endorsement from colleagues and mentors.

Each grant file includes a checklist of documents required to complete the application packet. In cases where there are several grant numbers for one individual, the application is located in the first file. Each file is subdivided as follows: Application; Award, Fund and Term Letters; Grant Data, including financial information; and Reports and Correspondence, which includes annual research reports submitted by the grantee and other correspondence pertaining to the status of the research project funded.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The files in this series are arranged alphabetically by the name of the institution. The Trust's administration alphabetized academic institutions based on the location. Thus, the University of Alabama is filed under Alabama.
Under each institution, the folders are arranged in the following sequence: General Correspondence, Denied Proposals, and Grant(s). Not every institution will have each type of folder noted here.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series includes material pertaining to grant awards and declinations. Each institutional history includes the initial contact with the Markey Trust and chronicles the decision to accept or deny the proposal submitted.

Depending upon individual appeals submitted to the Markey Trust, each institution represented will include one or more of the following folder types: General Correspondence, Denied Proposals, and Grant(s).

Materials in the General Correspondence folders include letters of a general nature, such as requests for information about program guidelines and details pertaining to grant application. Materials within these files are arranged chronologically.

Documents within the Denied Proposals folders are arranged by proposal number. The first two digits note the year of the proposal submission; the following numbers indicate the sequence of proposal submissions for that year from all institutions.

Information found in the Grant folders includes the documentation of the awarded grant proposal and the following sections: Proposal, Award and Funding Letters, Grant Data, and Reports and Correspondence. Within each section, documents are ordered chronologically.

Monographs which represent the published research of a number of organizational grants have not been microfilmed; however, they are housed in the Rockefeller Archive Center's library. The microfilmed collection includes a photocopy of each Title Page and Table of Contents in its place.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The records of the governing committees and Trust administration document policy decisions, financial accountability, program direction, and managerial aspects of Trust maintenance. Some Committees existed during a portion of the Trust's operation, and others were combined and reformed to accommodate the variation in the number of participating individuals.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged in five sections:
Section A - Co-Personal Representatives and the Investment Committee
Section D - Trustees Committee and Combined Trustees and Finance Committee
Section E - Combined Trustees, Finance Committee and Executive Committee
Each section is arranged chronologically by meeting date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The minutes found in this subseries document the Committee meetings held throughout the duration of the Trust's fifteen years of operation. These meetings were held in different locations in the United States. Numerous organizational meetings were held at the Trust's corporate headquarters in Miami, Florida in addition to meetings held in New York City; Chicago, Illinois; Menlo Park and Los Angeles, California; Denver and Colorado Springs, Colorado; Dallas, Texas; and Lexington, Kentucky, the site of Calumet Farms.
Only the Trustees and Executive Committees existed during the full fifteen-year operation of the Markey Trust.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This subseries includes correspondence, memoranda, and notes generated by Louis J. Hector, who served as the Chairman of the Board of the Markey Trust for the duration of the Trust's operation. Records include executive committee material, general correspondence, and trustee correspondence. Mr. Hector also maintained files pertaining to other Board members and special projects. Information pertaining to the origins and history of the Trust and the attempt to contract a written history is also documented. Trustees' and Officers' biographies are included in the series.

scopecontent.p: Information pertaining to Calumet Farm and the auction of its contents in 1992 are found in this subseries.
